abstract: Prof. Frederick Starr, after a thrilling fifteen months spent in the Congo studying the pigmy races, returned yesterday on the Red Star Line steamship Vaderland. Prof. Starr traveled more than 21,000 miles in his search for information. When last heard from, about six months ago, he was in the wilds, of Central Africa.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 31. -- The State Department has no official advices relative to the reported anti-American mass meeting at Canton. abstract: Fraudulent claims for sewer and water main damage to the amount of approximately $750,000 have been thrown out by the Finance Department of the city, according to a statement issued yesterday by Controller Metz. Many of these claims, as shown by the statement, were put in by William O. Miles, who was indicted in Kings County in connection with the claims, tried, convicted, and sentenced to imprisonment for one year.

abstract: NEW ORLEANS, Dec. 31. -- Three Jockeys fell with their mounts and two of them were severely injured during the third race at the Fair Grounds to-day. At the three-quarters pole, Expect-To-See fell, knocking Jockey Austin unconscious. The Scout fell over them, throwing and slightly injuring Jockey Noone, and Jockey Smith's collar bone was broken as his mount, Harry Gardiner, stumbled over the mess. Sir Mincemeat won the race by twelve lengths.

abstract: TOPEKA, Kan., Jan. 2. -- Thirty-five persons, all Mexicans but three, were killed early to-day in a head-on collision of two passenger trains of the Chicago, Rock Island  Pacific Railroad near Voland. abstract: WASHINGTON, Jan. 3. -- A second break in the Colorado River dam is reported to-day, and it seems probable that this will decide E.H. abstract: NEW ORLEANS, Jan. 4. -- The George D. Emery Company, composed of Boston people, is in trouble with the Government of Nicaragua and has asked that the United States Government send a warship to Bluefields to protect its interests. abstract: ALBANY, Jan. 4. -- Whether an ice famine will come again next Summer depends on the weather of the next few days. The warm spell and rainy period which set in last week has broken up the frozen surface of the Hudson River as far south as Coxsackie and north to Troy. The Mohawk ice also has broken up and moved down into the Hudson.

abstract: TO-MORROW the second and final session of the Fifty-ninth Congress will begin its work. Theoretically it began on the first Monday of December, but this is a pleasant fiction. Under the old but not venerable practice of Congress, the first month of a session is practically wasted. Nothing of any moment is done. Oratorical fireworks are set off, though in this case even that was omitted, unless Senator Foraker's Brownsville speech comes under that head.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Jan. 6. -- The year opened with the iron and steel markets decidedly strong in every line. abstract: BERLIN, Jan. 8. -- The most important meeting held so far in the political campaign, called by distinguished men in science and art, met to-night in the building of the University of Art and Music. abstract: Arthur J. O'Keeffe, First Deputy Police Commissioner, presided at the police trials yesterday for the first time since assuming the duties of his office. Weller of New York, from serious injury. McGraw was slightly bruised.

abstract: BUFFALO, N. Y., Jan. 10. -- The Milburn house. 1,816 Delaware Avenue, where President McKinley died, was partly destroyed by fire this morning. Those in the house were obliged to flee in their night clothes. The fire, it is believed, broke out in a cupboard under one corner of the room in which the President died. The room was somewhat damaged on the opposite side from where the President's bed stood.

abstract: France's money market is almost as much a marvel to the world as our own. abstract: As a matter of fact is not Charlotte Bronte an excellent example of the great need for a writer of travel, change of scene and mental atmosphere? Senator Dryden's managers are apparently disinclined formally to launch his candidacy till they have assured themselves that it will go through.

abstract: WILLIAMSPORT, Penn., Jan. 12. -- Probably the most powerful "outlaw" league the National Association of Professional Baseball Clubs was ever called upon to oppose has arisen from the ruins of the Tri-State League, which capitulated to organized baseball last week. Plans, quietly carried on for the last month, have resulted in the formation of an eight-club league, including Youngstown, Ohio; Elmira, N.Y., and Pittsburg, Williamsport, Lancaster, Reading, Wilkesbarre, and Scranton, Penn.

abstract: WEST POINT, N.Y., Jan. 12. -- The army basket ball team received its first defeat of the season to-day, Princeton doing the trick after hard work, by a score of 29 to 27. The play was the fastest seen here this year, and the first half ended with the score: Princeton, 14; Army, 12. With three minutes to play Rockwell tied the score at 24 points, and the excitement was intense.

abstract: The authorities at Columbia University made known yesterday an important change in the academic calendar. This has to do with the date for holding commencement. The plan is to lengthen the regular session and hold commencement before this is over. The day is fixed for the last Wednesday in May, the rule to go into effect at the close of the year 1907-08.

abstract: THE pure food law passed by Congress last Spring has been in operation two weeks, or since Jan. 1. Already the effects of it are amazing. The masquerade of alcohol, opium, cocaine, and other injurious drugs as nerve tonics or cures for stomach and lung diseases is at an end. Concoctions of spirits are no longer called whisky, or base syrups known as blackberry or strawberry jam, honey, refined molasses, or currant or raspberry jelly.

abstract: WHILE naturalists have speculated much as to the causes for the migration of birds, without being able to assign any positive reasons, yet one thing we do know -- that birds which spend the Winter as far south as the West Indies return to the same spot yearly to nest; that they often build their nests year after year within a few feet of the same spot.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Jan. 13. -- The body of Frank X. Delone, horseman, athlete, and clubman, was found this morning in the Schuylkill River near City Avenue Bridge. It is believed that the horse which he rode last Wednesday became unruly and threw him over the iron railing. If so, he fell 100 feet to the water.

abstract: While there was no public entry to the Automobile Show yesterday in Madison Square Garden, the big building was, nevertheless, the scene of considerable activity. A few French machines are still lacking and they will probably be cleared through the Custom House to-day.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., Jan. 13. -- The dangerous flood stage in the rivers here, which was anticipated to-day by the United States Weather Bureau authorities, failed to materialize, and to-night the stage of water is stationary after rising a little over twenty feet. While this stage caused considerable trouble in the lowlands, a twenty-two foot stage is necessary for a flood in the downtown section of the city.

abstract: CHICAGO, Jan. 13. -- The labor conference last night at Mrs. Potter Palmer's residence, 100 Lake Shore Drive, will bear its first fruit to-morrow. A meeting has been called to consider the establishment at once of a branch of the National Civic Federation in Chicago. It had not been planned to organize the branch so soon, but the success of the preliminary gathering led the promoters to decide that the time is ripe.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Jan. 16. -- Evidence offered in the Orphans' Court to-day showed that Congressman Robert H. Adams, Jr., who committed suic de in Washington last June, was a defaulter to the amount of $70,000, the money having come from the estate of his father, Robert Adams. The facts were known to members of the family since Mr. Adams's death, but were kept secret until an adjustment of the estate forced the disclosure.

abstract: A novelty in cycle races was introduced at the National Athletic Club last evening when Eddie Root and Joe Folger, winners of the six-day bicycle race in Madison Square Garden, raced against each other on home trainers. abstract: WASHINGTON. Jan. 16. -- Otto Seelhorst of 2927 Poplar Street, Philadelphia, to-day shot and instantly killed F. Von Iterson, an artist employed at the National Museum in this city. Incoherent remarks made by the murderer suggest a family feud of many years standing. These, together with irrational assertions made in what Seelhorst gave out as his "statement," suggest grave mental disorder on the part of the Philadelphian.

abstract: ST. PETERSBURG, Jan. 17. -- Gen. Arthur Tcherep Spiridovich, President of the Pan-Slavic League, is to leave here to-morrow for Washington to present to President Roosevelt on behalf of the league a cup for his services in bringing about the Portsmouth conference, as a result of which, according to the league, Russia has resumed her true mission of defender of Pan-Slavism.

abstract: ORMOND, Fla., Jan. 21. -- The Stanley steamer ran an exhibition mile favored by the wind on Daytona beach this afternoon just before dark in 0:38 3-5. Vanderbilt, Jr., made a mile in 39 seconds over the same stretch, the crowd went wild.

abstract: MIDDLETOWN, N.Y., Jan. 21. -- The old Dusinberre house, the oldest landmark in Southern New York, has been destroyed by fire. The house was situated near Edenville, Orange County. It was built in 1732 by Major Forobus Post. It was an inn when first erected, and being situated on the old turnpike between Newark and Newburg, was a favorite stopping place for Washington and other Generals of the Revolutionary War.

abstract: KINGSTON, Jamaica, Jan. 21. -- The indignation of the residents of Jamaica, both officials and private citizens, at the action of Gov. Swettenham in demanding the withdrawal by Admiral Davis of the American relief forces is spreading and intensifying. abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., Jan. 23. -- Twice dragged beneath the waters of Lake Whitney in his attempt to pull from the water Miss Jennie Toumey, Buckingham Miller of Newton Highlands, Mass., a Yale freshman, made a dangerous rescue this afternoon. abstract: A generation ago there was a general clamor because Congress voted itself an increase of pay from $5,000 to $7,500 a year. The clamor was so general and persistent that Congress fled before it. In January, 1874, it precipitately repealed the act of March, 1873. Now, the same increase is voted without, so far as we have noticed, creating any popular clamor at all.

abstract: KINGSTON, Tuesday, Jan. 22, (Delayed.) -- Gov. Swettenham has written another letter to Admiral Davis in Cuba thanking him for his aid. The Governor also expresses regret that his scruples would not allow him to accept more of the Admiral's help. He says that he trusts that on a future occasion he will have the pleasure of meeting Admiral Davis and of according him the honor due to his rank and station.

abstract: The development of the art of printing and bookbinding in London from 1476 to 1535 is described in the new volume by E. Gordon Duff, sometime Sandars Reader in Bibliography in the University of Cambridge, England. abstract: " Johnny" Hein, the diminutive champion wrestler of the Boys' Club, distinguished himself last night in the final bouts of the Inter-Settlement championship meeting in the gymnasium of the Boys' Club. Hein won in the 115-pound class over G. Malinger, his classmate. The winner of National honors at St. Louis was very quick, and after Malinger had nearly pinned him Hein quickly secured a half-nelson and leg hold, and took the bout in 3:32.

abstract: BERLIN, Jan. 25. -- The Government has won a definite victory in the general elections held to-day for a new Reichstag. The Liberal, Radical, and Conservative Parites, supporting Prince von Buelow's colonial policy, have won at least twenty seats, but more important for the Government than the success of its colonial plans is the smashing defeat administered to the Socialists, who will lose a total of seventeen or eighteen seats.

abstract: COLOMBO, Jan. 27. -- The North German Lloyd Line steamer Seydlitz, Capt. abstract: ALBANY, Jan. 29. -- Three bills were introduced in the Assembly to-day by Assemblyman Duell of Westchester, providing for amendments to the insurance and banking laws which if enacted, would considerably broaden the powers of investment on the part of such corporations. abstract: WORCESTER, Mass., Jan. 29. -- The three Maxwell cars which are making the comparative fuel test tour from New York to Boston reached this city at 5 o'clock this evening after a hard run from Hartford. abstract: ALBANY, Jan. 29. -- The Economic Power and Construction Company of Albany to-day filed in the County Clerk's office a mortgage to the New York Security Company for $250,000 on its franchise and property. abstract: The Gridiron Club of Washington is without doubt called after the familiar culinary implement of the same name. abstract: When President DIAZ pressed the button at Salina Cruz the other day, he started a competition which will never end. It will be as impossible for the Panama Canal to put the Tehuantepec route out of business as that the contrary should happen. Doubtless there will be room for both, but the fact should be recognized from the beginning that the Mexican route has certain advantages which are as incontestable as the American's.

abstract: In the cut twenty feet deep through which trains between New York and Coney Island on the Brighton Beach Division of the Brooklyn Rapid Transit now run two trains came together at 6:50 o'clock last night a few yards north of the Newkirk Avenue station. Three cars were derailed, two almost overturned, and the third crushed beneath a heavy wooden bridge which the force of the collision shook down from its position across the cut.

abstract: PALM BEACH, Fla., Jan. 30. -- One of the strangest motor boat accidents in the history of Lake Worth occurred at noon to-day. Two fine gasoline boats collided and were destroyed, and Mrs. James King Clarke of Philadelphia narrowly escaped with her life. Her skirts caught in the machinery displaced by the collision, and had to be cut away before she could be assisted to one of the boats near by.

abstract: I read with interest the curiously misleading letter from Mr. Michael Monahan, printed In THE TIMES of Monday. abstract: WASHINGTON, Jan. 30. -- Congressman Burton, as Chairman of the Rivers and Harbors Committee, brought in to-day what he is determined shall be his last river and harbor bill in the House. His speech on that bill to-morrow will be, in a sense, his valedictory after twelve years of remarkable service to the cause of internal improvements.
